definition.value: A monoterpenoid formally derived from beta-cyclocitral by dehydrogenation.

HNK-1 (human natural killer-1) carbohydrate (a glycoheptaosylceramide), is characteristically expressed on a series of cell adhesion molecules in the nervous system. The HNK-1 carbohydrate has a unique structural feature, i.e. a sulfated glucuronic acid is attached to the non-reducing terminal of an N-acetyllactosamine residue (HSO3-3GlcA-beta-(1->3)-Gal-beta-(1->4)-GlcNAc-).
A 1,12-dialdehyde compound having double bonds in the 2-, 4-, 6-, 8-, and 10-positions and methyl substituents in the 4- and 9-positions.
A 1,12-diol compound having double bonds in the 2-, 4-, 6-, 8-, and 10-positions.
A beta-ionone compound having an (R)-hydroxy group at the 3-position.
A five-membered cyclic dicarboximide compound having a bromo substituent on the nitrogen atom.
An apo carotenoid compound arising from oxidative degradation of the beta,beta-carotene skeleton at the 13-position.
A 1,8-dialdehyde compound having double bonds in the 2-, 4- and 6-positions and a methyl substituent at the 4-position.
A monoterpenoid formally derived from citral by cyclisation. It is a volatile compound produced by a cyanobacteria.
A norterpene that is an acyclic saturated hydrocarbon derived from phytane by loss of its C-16 terminal methyl group.
Any hydrocarbon formed by loss of a methyl group from a terpene.
A compound arising from loss of part of the carotene skeleton (excluding retinoids)
A C25 terpenoid compound arising from loss of part of the carotene skeleton.
A C35 terpenoid compound arising from loss of part of the carotene skeleton.
A diterpenoid compound arising from loss of part of the carotene skeleton.
A uranium coordination entity consisting of uranium(V) bound to two pentamethylcyclopentadienyl groups, a 2,6-diisopropylanilino group (via a U=N bond) and a phenylselenyl group.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of dexverapamil hydrochloride and (S)-verapamil hydrochloride.
A C14 fatty-acyl group having a (Z)-double bond at the 7-position.
A C18 fatty-acyl group having a triple bond at the 7-position.
A uranium coordination entity consisting of uranium(V) bound to two pentamethylcyclopentadienyl groups, a 2,6-diisopropylanilino group (via a U=N bond) and a phenylthio group.
A compound of the general formula RSO2-N=C(OR1)R2 where R, R1 and R2 can be H or organyl.
An N-sulfonylimidate compound having S-methyl and O-phenyl substituents.
A macromolecule prepared from aniline or a substituted aniline.
A macromolecule composed of aniline units connected by amine bonds.
A polyaniline macromolecule composed of aniline units connected by imine bonds.
A macromolecule composed of aniline units linked by alternating imine and amine bonds.
A macromolecule composed of repeating imino-1,4-phenylene units.
A polymer composed of amino (-NH2) and amido  (-C(=O)NH-) units.
A homopolymer macromolecule, prepared from epsilon-caprolactone.
A macromolecule with functional groups linked by carbonate (-O-(C=O)-O-) groups.
A macromolecule composed of bisphenol A units connected by carbonate (-O-(C=O)-O-)  groups.
A five-membered cyclic dicarboximide compound having a chloro substituent on the nitrogen atom.
A five-membered cyclic dicarboximide compound having an iodo substituent on the nitrogen atom.
A macromolecule composed of repeating methyl methacrylate units.
A tetradecenoic acid having a cis-double bond at the 7-position.
A seco retinoid formed by fission of the cyclohexene ring with addition of a hydrogen atom at each terminal group thus created.
An S-alkyl thiosulfate having 2-(dimethylamino)ethyl as the alkyl group.
A quaternary ammonium salt having tetrapropylammonium as the cation and perruthenate as the anion.
An optically active O-acylcarnitine compound having propanoyl as the acyl substituent and (R)-configuration at the 3-position.
An O-acyl-D-carnitine in which  the acyl group specified is propanoyl.
Organonitrogen compounds that are derivatives of isocyanic acid; compounds containing the isocyanate functional group -N=C=O (as opposed to the cyanate group, -O-C#N).
An isocyanate compound containing two isocyanate functional groups. Manufactured for reaction with polyols in the production of polyurethanes.
A diisocyanate in which the two isocyanate groups are linked by an isophorone substituent.
A carotenone compound arising from oxidative cleavage of the 5',6'-double bond.
A diisocyanate consisting of dicyclohexylmethane with two isocyanate groups at the 4- and 4'-positions.
An apo carotenoid compound arising from oxidative degradation of the beta,beta-carotene skeleton at the 1'- and 6'-positions.
